## TL;DR: 3 Carat Princess Cut Diamond Price — Key Facts

- **Only one GIA 3ct princess on Blue Nile:** [GIA 3.00ct G-VVS2 Ideal Cut at $41,095](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29206996?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). One option. No grade flexibility. No alternative.
- **vs. Round at 3ct:** A [3ct GIA round G-VS2](/3-carat-round-diamond-price) costs $48,780 on Blue Nile. The princess saves you $7,685 — 15.7% less — while delivering one clarity grade higher (VVS2 vs VS2).
- **3.5ct opens three options:** GIA 3.53ct G-VS2 at $48,445, GIA 3.53ct G-IF at $51,448, and GIA 3.51ct G-VVS2 at $60,554. For $7,350 more than the 3ct stone, you gain 0.53ct and real selection.
- **VS1 is mandatory at 3ct:** This is not aesthetic preference — it is structural. Corner inclusions in a 3ct princess carry fracture risk under daily impact. VS2 at 3ct is a gamble I will not recommend.
- **The 4ct Per-Carat Cliff:** The next GIA princess above 3.5ct on Blue Nile is a [4.22ct G-VS1 at $96,590](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/13275667?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) — $22,890 per carat vs $13,698 per carat at 3ct. That is a 67% per-carat jump for 1.22 more carats.
- **Contrarian Truth:** Every "3ct princess" article shows stunning stone images and aspirational price ranges. What they omit: at exactly 3.00 carats, Blue Nile has one GIA stone. If that stone does not fit your grade target, color preference, or proportion requirements — you are not buying a 3ct princess. You are buying a 3.5ct princess (three options) or rethinking the shape entirely. The "3ct princess market" is a single stone, not a market.
- See **The 3ct Rarity Lock** and **The 4ct Per-Carat Cliff** breakdowns below.

