## The 3ct Rarity Lock: Why Blue Nile Has Only One GIA 3-Carat Princess

At exactly 3.00 carats, GIA-certified Ideal Cut princess diamonds are nearly absent from major retailers. This is not a supply disruption. It is how the princess cut market works at large sizes.

Blue Nile's current inventory contains one GIA princess at 3.00 carats: the [G-VVS2 Ideal at $41,095](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29206996?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). At the same 3ct weight, Blue Nile lists 15+ GIA round brilliant diamonds in G-VS2 alone, ranging from $44,500 to $84,710. The princess cut is structurally rarer in large formats.

Three factors compound to create this rarity. Princess cutting requires rough crystals with specific octahedral geometry — the larger the intended stone, the harder it becomes to source compliant rough. Princess cuts also require more rough per finished carat than rounds, because the four corners demand precise flat-plane alignment. Finally, Ideal Cut princess grading at 3ct imposes strict proportion tolerances that further narrow the qualifying pool. The result is what I call **The 3ct Rarity Lock**: virtually zero grade selection at the 3.00ct mark.

**Farzana's translation:** The 3ct Rarity Lock is not temporary. It reflects the market structure of large princess rough. If your grade preference for this budget is G-VS1 or F-VS2 — those stones do not exist as GIA princess cuts at 3ct on Blue Nile. Your real choices are: buy the one available G-VVS2 stone, size up to 3.5ct (three GIA options), or switch to round (broad selection at 3ct). All three are valid paths — but you need to know the lock exists before you walk in.

