## 3ct Princess vs 3ct Round: Which Is Cheaper and What You Give Up

At 3 carats, the princess cut is meaningfully cheaper than round — with a real face-up trade-off. Here is the full comparison.

| Metric | 3ct Princess (G-VVS2) | 3ct Round (G-VS2) | Difference |
|---|---|---|---|
| Price | $41,095 | $48,780 | Princess saves **$7,685** |
| Savings % | — | — | **15.7% less** for princess |
| Clarity | VVS2 | VS2 | Princess is one clarity grade higher |
| Face-up size | ~8.1×8.1mm | ~9.4mm diameter | Round is ~5.5% larger face-up area |
| Per carat | $13,698 | $16,260 | Princess saves $2,562 per carat |
| GIA options | 1 stone | 15+ stones | Round has vastly more selection |
| Setting required | V-tip prongs mandatory | Standard prongs work | Princess setting is more specific |

The $7,685 savings is real. At 3ct price levels, $7,685 pays for a premium platinum 4-prong V-tip setting, a matching diamond eternity band, or a whole clarity tier upgrade in a different stone. The savings compound into meaningful downstream choices.

The grade advantage makes the comparison even more interesting: the 3ct princess is VVS2 clarity at $41,095. The comparable 3ct round at $48,780 is VS2. You are getting a higher clarity grade for $7,685 less. That combination — lower price, higher clarity — is unusual and worth calling out.

![3ct princess vs round price and face-up size — The Statement Square](/images/3-carat-princess-vs-round-comparison.avif "3ct Princess Cut vs Round: Price, Face-Up Size, and Clarity Comparison")

The face-up area trade-off is real but moderate. A 3ct round at 9.4mm diameter has approximately 69.4mm² face-up area. A 3ct princess at ~8.1mm per side has approximately 65.6mm² — about 5.5% less. In a ring on a hand at conversational distance, that difference is not dramatic. It is visible in a side-by-side comparison but not apparent in photos or across a table.

**Farzana's translation:** At 3ct, the princess cut saves you real money for a better clarity grade. The face-up area penalty is the smallest per-dollar trade-off in the comparison. What the princess gives you that round cannot: 90-degree corners that create sharp architectural geometry visible from 10 feet away. That visual character — **The Statement Square** — is the reason you choose princess over round at 3ct, not just the savings. See the [round diamond vs princess cut guide](/round-diamond-vs-princess-cut) for the full shape comparison.

