## The Corner Fracture Rule: Why VS1 Is Mandatory at 3 Carats

VS1 at 3ct is not about aesthetics. It is about structural integrity. Here is why.

The four corners of a princess cut are the shape's structural weak points. Every princess cut ring requires 4-prong V-tip settings or full bezel protection specifically because these corners are fragile under impact. At 1ct, a corner inclusion reduces safety margin but rarely causes catastrophic failure. At 3ct, the physics change: a larger stone mass concentrates proportionally more force at corner tips during impact events — dropping a hand onto a countertop, a car door, a gym weight. A VS2 inclusion positioned at or near a corner tip in a 3ct stone becomes a crack initiation site under realistic daily conditions.

Here is the clarity risk scale specifically at 3ct for princess cut:

| Clarity | Eye-Clean at 3ct | Corner Safety | Farzana's Verdict |
|---------|-----------------|---------------|-------------------|
| VVS1 and above | 100% | Excellent | Overspec; safe corners; no visible benefit over VVS2 |
| VVS2 | 100% | Excellent | The G-VVS2 at $41,095 clears this standard perfectly |
| VS1 | 100% | Safe — verify corner placement | **Mandatory minimum for 3ct princess** |
| VS2 | ~50–60% | Risky — corner inclusions disqualifying | Acceptable only if GIA plot confirms inclusions are centered away from all four corners |
| SI1 | ~15–20% | No | Never at 3ct. Full stop. |
| SI2 | ~0–5% | No | Never |

![3ct princess corner clarity and VS1 rule — The Corner Fracture Rule](/images/3-carat-princess-corner-clarity-rule.avif "The Corner Fracture Rule: VS1 Is the Structural Minimum at 3ct Princess")

The single GIA 3ct stone on Blue Nile is G-VVS2. It passes The Corner Fracture Rule with margin to spare. VVS2 inclusions are microscopic and never near corners in any GIA-certified VVS2 stone. If you step up to the [3.53ct G-VS2 at $48,445](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29185768?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational), request the GIA plot and confirm VS2 inclusions are centered in the stone — any inclusion within 2mm of a corner is a disqualifying factor at this price point.

**Farzana's translation:** I have evaluated hundreds of princess cut diamonds. The corner fracture question is the one I take most seriously at 3ct+. A $41,095 stone with a corner fracture from a routine impact is not a warranty claim scenario — it is a catastrophic loss. VS1 minimum, corner-plot verified, V-tip prongs. That is the checklist. Everything else is secondary.

For clarity fundamentals across all sizes, see the [VS1 clarity guide](/vs1-clarity-diamonds) and the [princess cut diamond guide](/princess-cut-diamond).

