| 3.53ct G-VS2 | [View →](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29185768?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) | $48,445 | ~8.5×8.5mm | $13,723 | +$7,350 / +0.53ct / +0.4mm side |
| 3.53ct G-IF | [View →](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28075445?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) | $51,448 | ~8.5×8.5mm | $14,576 | +$10,353 / +0.53ct / slightly steep per-carat |
| 3.51ct G-VVS2 | [View →](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/25553411?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) | $60,554 | ~8.5×8.5mm | $17,252 | +$19,459 / same grade as 3ct / significant premium |

The [3.53ct G-VS2 at $48,445](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29185768?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the compelling choice. It costs $7,350 more than the 3ct G-VVS2, adds 0.53ct of natural diamond, and delivers approximately 0.4mm more side length per face. The per-carat rate is $13,723 — just $25 more than the 3ct rate of $13,698. You are paying for additional weight, not a rarity premium.

The [3.51ct G-VVS2 at $60,554](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/25553411?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is harder to justify. You are paying $19,459 more than the 3ct stone for the same G-VVS2 grade and 0.51ct additional weight. That works out to $38,155 per additional carat — well above the market rate. This stone is priced in rarity premium territory, not proportional value territory.

**Farzana's recommendation:** If your budget allows $48,000–$50,000, the 3.53ct G-VS2 at $48,445 is the better purchase over the 3ct G-VVS2 at $41,095. The $7,350 difference buys you 0.53ct more stone at essentially the same per-carat rate, more face-up presence, and genuine selection (you can inspect the GIA certificate and choose vs accepting the only available 3ct option). The upgrade math works. If your budget is strictly $41,000–$43,000, the G-VVS2 at $41,095 is an excellent stone and the only path at exactly 3ct.

