## How Lab-Grown Compares at 3 Carats: The 85% Price Gap

The lab-grown comparison at 3ct princess is the most extreme price differential in this guide.

A lab-grown 3ct D-VVS1 IGI princess on major retailers typically prices between $3,500 and $6,000 in {{year}}. Against the natural 3ct G-VVS2 at $41,095, that is an 85–91% price reduction for a stone with identical face-up dimensions and superior paper grades (D vs G color, VVS1 vs VVS2 clarity). The price gap is not subtle — it is $35,000–$37,000 in absolute dollars.

The trade-off is resale value and natural origin. Natural diamonds at 3ct resell at approximately 40–50 cents on the dollar — a $41,095 stone has eventual resale value of $16,000–$20,000. Lab-grown diamonds resell at 10–20 cents on the dollar — a $5,000 lab stone yields $500–$1,000 at resale. The resale advantage of natural is real. But the $35,000 initial savings on the lab path far exceeds that resale differential for any buyer who plans to wear the ring rather than liquidate it within five years.

For buyers who care about appearance and budget, the lab path is overwhelming at 3ct. For buyers who care about natural origin, rarity, and long-term asset value — the single G-VVS2 at $41,095 remains the only GIA natural 3ct option. Blue Nile's lab pricing and selection in princess format is covered in the [princess cut diamond guide](/princess-cut-diamond).

