| 3.53ct G-VS2 | [View →](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29185768?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) | $48,445 | $13,723 | +$25 (+0.2%) |
| 4.22ct G-VS1 | [View →](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/13275667?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) | $96,590 | $22,890 | **+$9,192 (+67%)** |
| 5.05ct F-VS2 | [View →](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29242302?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) | $125,167 | $24,786 | +$11,088 (+81%) |
| 5.01ct D-VS2 | [View →](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/19070016?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) | $141,294 | $28,202 | +$14,504 (+106%) |
| 5.60ct G-IF | [View →](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/15813387?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) | $278,753 | $49,777 | +$36,079 (+264%) |

**The 4ct Per-Carat Cliff** is the pricing inflection point I identified in the Blue Nile large princess inventory. Per-carat cost holds at $13,698–$13,723 across the entire 3ct to 3.5ct range — essentially flat. Then it jumps to $22,890 at 4ct. That 67% per-carat increase for 1.22 additional carats reflects the exponential rarity of 4ct+ princess rough and the difficulty of achieving Ideal Cut standards at larger sizes.

At 5ct, you are paying $24,786–$49,777 per carat — up to 3.6× the per-carat rate of the 3ct stone. The 5.60ct G-IF at $278,753 is pricing in both rarity and clarity at a level where per-carat cost has decoupled from linear weight progression entirely. The identical cliff dynamic exists in round diamonds — see the [3 carat round diamond price guide](/3-carat-round-diamond-price) — but in princess format the cliff is steeper because large princess rough is rarer than equivalent round rough.

**Farzana's translation:** 3ct is the last affordable tier in large GIA princess diamonds. Every carat above 3.5ct costs dramatically more per unit of diamond than the carat below it. If you want maximum GIA princess per dollar, the 3ct and 3.5ct range is the target. Above that, you are paying a rarity premium that compounds aggressively. This is not a reason to avoid 4ct+ stones — it is a reason to understand what you are actually paying for at each size step.

